<paragraph blockId="15.[164,779,1056,1353]" pageId="15" pageNumber="712">
<emphasis box="[164,588,1056,1078]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="712">
Taxonomic notes: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Townsend" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[372,588,1056,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="712" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fornax">Copestylum fornax</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is more similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Osten Sacken" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[200,299,1087,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="712" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="satur">
<emphasis box="[200,299,1087,1108]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="712">C. satur</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Williston" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[418,615,1087,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="712" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraudulentum">
<emphasis box="[418,615,1087,1108]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="712">C. fraudulentum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Williston" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[321,512,1117,1138]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="712" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraudulentum">
<emphasis box="[321,512,1117,1138]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="712">C. fraudulentum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shallow TR and vestiture confined to medial areas of abdominal transverse folds. It is separated from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Osten Sacken" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[560,657,1179,1200]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="712" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="satur">
<emphasis box="[560,657,1179,1200]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="712">C. satur</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a redbrown, nontapering AP which is the same length as a pupal spiracle, the shorter, 1.5¥ basal width pupal spiracles which are separated by more than 4¥ their length and by the more complex curves of the spiracular openings.
</paragraph>
